name: Edward Snowden
tweet:
@PaulDiegel In 2013, I warned of "turnkey tyranny." At the time, many laughed, but who could blame them? They were not technologists—they could not yet grasp the scale of the coming disruption.

Few laugh now.

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @PaulDiegel In Washington, London, Beijing, and Moscow, a huge fraction of the leadership communicates using iPhones and similarly vulnerable devices—alongside everyone that leadership associates with. This market, unchecked, will very soon democratize access to monitoring those devices.

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @PaulDiegel The idea that the great powers of our era are interested in Azerbaijian attaining strategic parity in intelligence gathering is, of course, profoundly mistaken. They simply have yet to fully grasp the threat, because the capability gap has not vanished—yet.

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @PaulDiegel The slogan is simple: if companies are not divested, the owners should be arrested. The exclusive product of this industry is intentional, foreseeable harm. These companies are active participants.

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @PaulDiegel Finally, it is crucial to understand that NSO's business would not have been possible at the scale it is today—nor the consequences it has inflicted on global society—without access to global capital from amoral firms like Novalpina Capital (Europe) and Francisco Partners (US).

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @PaulDiegel The most reckless hacking campaigns—such as those fueled by NSO's sales to autocrats—leave evidence that in time is often discovered. Even if Israel will not extradite those responsible, international civil and criminal liability imposes real costs, and prevents travel.

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @PaulDiegel We cannot stop governments from engaging in homegrown hacking. But we can with relative ease halt the international commercial market for the intrusion software that permit anyone with a few million euro under their desk to infect every iPhone in the world.

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @PaulDiegel We have done it before, in the case of the CBRN regulation, and it (largely) works even without universal observance, bc other states face the same risks from proliferation. Moratorium is merely triage—stops the bleeding, creating space for monitoring and enforcement.

name: Edward Snowden

name: Edward Snowden
tweet:
How else can NSO's country-code targeting prohibition be bypassed? Simple:

1) Target a specially-prepared device *you control* in an eligible country code

2) Forensically capture each exploit stage as it's served to your trap device

3) Reverse it

4) Retarget anyone, anywhere

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @mcelhearn This question breaks down to "if I have a phone, and make the PIN 1234567890, is it secure?" At best, GrayKey et al can permit unlimited unlock *attempts*. If you choose a secure passphrase instead of a short, weak PIN, the Sun will burn out before GrayKey unlocks your phone.

name: Edward Snowden
tweet: @ryanol The general security principle is that if you can look at something on your unlocked phone without entering a password, obviously anyone else who has your unlocked phone can do the same. We don't call that "breaking crypto," we call that obvious.
